{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"45d4fadb-8e97-4928-a980-d4e245086bdd","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n}\n```\n\n**Why switch?**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor throwing instead of `CreateUser`).\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pinpoints exactly which call should throw.\n- You can also capture and inspect the exception:\n\n```csharp\nvar ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n    () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\nAssert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"57dadfc7-7836-4951-bf21-cb2b229d7462","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a straightforward knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":273,"requestId":"7C1B:21DC3D:273F62A:2B8F9DB:69F946E4"},"id":"7ba6afd2-eb1c-4b74-b542-2925e3483761","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:24:59.412Z","parentId":"98969b46-fbc2-4029-ad3f-9bb0973efb59"}
